<div id="notsogoodbutok" class="xar-mod-body">
<h3><xar:mlstring>Report generator module</xar:mlstring></h3>
<p>
    <xar:mlstring>
        This module generates reports based on data accessible to the module over
        a certain connection to a database. By using a report definition in XSL-FO,
        the module generates reports in HTML or PDF format.
    </xar:mlstring>
</p>
<p>
    <xar:mlstring>
        The XSL-FO format is a generic XML dialect for describing (paginated) documents.
        Using blocklayout and a little help from the module we add dynamism to the
        documents, which is the definition of a <em>report</em> in this module.
    </xar:mlstring>
</p>
<p>
    <xar:mlstring>
        The PDF output is generated using Apache's FOP program and the HTML output is
        generated using a XSL transformation stylesheet. This leads to the following
        requirements for this module:
    </xar:mlstring>
    <ol>
        <li><xar:mlstring>It can only be run on a server where FOP is installed, hence java must be available</xar:mlstring></li>
        <li><xar:mlstring>The server configuration must allow a system call to fop by the webserver process</xar:mlstring></li>
        <li><xar:mlstring>The xslt extension of PHP (Optional)</xar:mlstring></li>
    </ol>
</p>

<h4><xar:mlstring>Rough roadmap (unordered)</xar:mlstring></h4>
<ul>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Support calling FOP through the embedded java interface as an option</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Make it easy to upload report definitions (using the uploads module for example)</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li>
        <xar:mlstring>
            Implement a cache-ing mechanism for generated reports (or rather, re-use
            the output cache functionality xarcachemanager provides)
        </xar:mlstring>
    </li>
    <li>
        <xar:mlstring>
            XSL FO and the output agnostic wish we have for xar templates coincide
            nicely here, we can add generic xar tags in this module first
            and optionally promote them into blocklayout ( &gt; version 2.x ) when we
            are happy with their behaviour
        </xar:mlstring>
    </li>
    <li>
        <xar:mlstring>
            Replace the report specific data(-set) tags with the DD tag equivalents,
            because they really do exactly the same. (only the ones in this module are uglier)
        </xar:mlstring>
    </li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Track FOP developments closely, there is a lot of movement there</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Include a reference report demonstrating the possibilities and limitations</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li>
        <xar:mlstring>
            Think of something clever to include search capability in
            a better way without losing the option of easy report definition distribution.
        </xar:mlstring>
    </li>
</ul>

<h4><xar:mlstring>Usage scenarios</xar:mlstring></h4>
<p>
    <xar:mlstring>
        The purpose of this module is to generate very precisely formatted documents which
        are structured, i.e. can be automatically generated over and over again, based
        on a set of data which already exists. Typical report-types would be: invoices, sales reports,
        data analysis results, stock lists, BOM lists etc.
    </xar:mlstring>
</p>

<h4><xar:mlstring>WARNING</xar:mlstring></h4>
<p>
    <xar:mlstring>
        This module is not for the occasional XML user. If you do need to google for
        XSL-FO first to see what it is, dont bother using this module at this time.
        Come back a little later when we have encapsulated the complexities behind a nice
        GUI. ;-)
    </xar:mlstring>
</p>
